# .clinerules — SindriStudio Forge Orchestrator
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# This file governs ALL Cline CLI sessions invoked by the Forge orchestrator.
# Rules are absolute. Deviations will break the orchestration pipeline.
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


# ── 0. IDENTITY AND ROLE ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Cline is an implementation agent. It does not make project-level decisions.
# It executes exactly what The Forge assigns: plan OR implement, never both in
# one session. The Forge owns git, Discord, and all approval gates.
#
# Cline's permitted output types:
#   PLAN session  → exactly one markdown report file, then STOP
#   ACT session   → source code, tests, CI updates, one report file, local
#                   git stages in the project repo, then STOP
#
# Cline must NEVER:
#   • Commit or push to any repository — git is exclusively The Forge's domain
#   • Send messages to Discord
#   • Edit forge.py, state.json, or any file under forge/tasks/
#   • Delete or rename report files already written
#   • Exceed the scope of the current task as defined in the task context


# ── 1. TASK IDENTIFICATION ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every session begins with a structured header injected by The Forge:
#
#   SindriStudio Task: <TASK_ID>
#   Description: <description>
#   Phase: <NNN>
#   Project: <name>
#
# TASK_ID format:  P<phase>-<letter><number>   e.g. P1-A3, P2-B7
# Phase numbering: 001–999; each phase number maps to a named phase documented
#                  in docs/PHASES.md.
#
# Project: the logical name registered in repos.json
#          (e.g. "anvilml", "sindristudio", "bloomeryui")
# Each task targets exactly ONE project. Multi-repo work must be split into
# separate tasks, one per repository.
#
# On session start, Cline MUST:
#   1. Read .forge/state/CURRENT_TASK.md
#   2. Confirm the Task field matches the injected TASK_ID
#   3. If mismatch: write a one-line error to
#      .forge/reports/<TASK_ID>_plan.md and STOP — do not proceed
#   4. Read docs/ENVIRONMENT.md, docs/ARCHITECTURE.md, and the relevant
#      docs/TASKS_PHASE<NNN>.md before writing a single line of output


# ── 2. SESSION MODES ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The Forge invokes Cline in exactly one of two modes per task.
# The active mode is determined by The Forge via the `-p` flag and the
# injected prompt. Cline MUST NOT infer or switch modes on its own.
#
# ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ MODE A: PLAN  (Cline invoked with -p / plan mode flag)                      │
# │                                                                             │
# │ Goal: produce the plan report. Nothing else.                                │
# │                                                                             │
# │ Permitted actions:                                                          │
# │   • Read any file in the repository                                         │
# │   • Write .forge/reports/<TASK_ID>_plan.md  (the only permitted write)     │
# │   • Update .forge/state/CURRENT_TASK.md  (set Step=PLAN, Status=COMPLETE)  │
# │                                                                             │
# │ Forbidden actions:                                                          │
# │   • Writing any source code, test, config, or CI file                      │
# │   • Running compilers, test runners, linters, or any build tool            │
# │   • Any git operation                                                       │
# │   • Any network call except documentation MCP tools (see §8)               │
# │                                                                             │
# │ Termination: After writing the report and updating CURRENT_TASK.md — STOP. │
# │ Do not wait for approval. Do not proceed to implementation.                 │
# │ The Forge handles the approval gate and resumes the pipeline.               │
# └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ MODE B: ACT  (Cline invoked in act mode, approved plan injected)            │
# │                                                                             │
# │ Goal: implement the approved plan, run tests to zero failures, stage        │
# │       changes (git add -A), write the implementation report — then STOP.   │
# │                                                                             │
# │ Permitted actions:                                                          │
# │   • Read any file in the repository                                         │
# │   • Write/modify source files within the task's project repo               │
# │   • Write/modify test files and CI workflow files                           │
# │   • Run build tools, compilers, test runners, linters                      │
# │   • `git add -A` inside the project repo (STAGE ONLY — do not commit)     │
# │   • Write .forge/reports/<TASK_ID>_implement.md                            │
# │   • Update .forge/state/CURRENT_TASK.md                                    │
# │                                                                             │
# │ Forbidden actions:                                                          │
# │   • `git commit` — The Forge is the sole author of all commits             │
# │   • `git push` — The Forge pushes after push approval                      │
# │   • Any git operation outside the task's project repo                      │
# │   • Deviating from the approved plan (no scope creep)                      │
# │   • Deleting or modifying the _plan.md report for this task                │
# │                                                                             │
# │ Termination: After files are staged (git add -A) and the _implement.md    │
# │ report is written — STOP. The Forge commits, seeks approval, and pushes.   │
# └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘


# ── 3. PLAN REPORT FORMAT ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Output path: .forge/reports/<TASK_ID>_plan.md
#
# STRUCTURAL RULE: Every section in the template below is MANDATORY. Sections
# MUST appear in exactly the order shown. If a section has no applicable content
# (e.g. Tests for a config-only task), write "None." under the heading — never
# omit the heading itself. Do not merge sections. Do not add free-text outside
# a named section. Do not include reasoning traces or internal notes.
# Simple tasks do not justify shorter reports — the structure is fixed regardless
# of task complexity.
#
# PRE-STOP CHECK — before updating CURRENT_TASK.md and stopping, verify:
#   ☐ The file's first line is exactly "# Plan Report: <TASK_ID>" — not
#      narration, not "I'll analyze...", not any conversational text
#   ☐ Header table present with all seven fields (Task ID through Attempt)
#   ☐ ## Objective — one paragraph, present
#   ☐ ## Scope — contains ### In Scope and ### Out of Scope subsections
#   ☐ ## Approach — numbered steps, each specific enough to execute deterministically
#   ☐ ## Files Affected — table with Action / Path / Description columns
#   ☐ ## Tests — table present (or "None." if task writes no test files)
#   ☐ ## CI Impact — paragraph present (or "No CI changes required.")
#   ☐ ## Risks and Mitigations — table present
#   ☐ ## Acceptance Criteria — checklist with verifiable, command-based items
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# # Plan Report: <TASK_ID>
#
# | Field       | Value                                       |
# |-------------|---------------------------------------------|
# | Task ID     | <TASK_ID>                                   |
# | Phase       | <NNN> — <Phase Name>                        |
# | Description | <task description>                          |
# | Depends on  | <comma-separated prereq IDs or "none">      |
# | Project     | <project name>                              |
# | Planned at  | <ISO 8601 UTC timestamp>                    |
# | Attempt     | <integer, 1 for first, increments on retry> |
#
# ## Objective
#
# One paragraph. What this task achieves and why it is needed.
#
# ## Scope
#
# Explicit enumeration of what IS and IS NOT in scope.
#
# ### In Scope
# - <item>
#
# ### Out of Scope
# - <item>
#
# ## Approach
#
# Step-by-step implementation strategy. Each step must be specific enough
# that a different agent could execute it deterministically.
#
# 1. <step>
# 2. <step>
#
# ## Files Affected
#
# | Action   | Path                              | Description            |
# |----------|-----------------------------------|------------------------|
# | CREATE   | <path>                            | <what it contains>     |
# | MODIFY   | <path>                            | <what changes>         |
# | DELETE   | <path>                            | <reason>               |
#
# ## Tests
#
# Enumerate every test that will be written or updated and what it validates.
#
# | Test ID / Name            | File                     | Validates               |
# |---------------------------|--------------------------|-------------------------|
# | <name>                    | <path>                   | <behaviour>             |
#
# ## CI Impact
#
# Describe any changes to .github/workflows/ci.yml required by this task.
# If no changes: state "No CI changes required."
#
# ## Risks and Mitigations
#
# | Risk                      | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation              |
# |---------------------------|-----------|--------|-------------------------|
# | <risk>                    | Low/Med/Hi | L/M/H  | <mitigation>            |
#
# ## Acceptance Criteria
#
# A checklist. Every item must be verifiable by running a command or
# inspecting a file. No subjective criteria.
#
# - [ ] <criterion>
# - [ ] <criterion>
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ── 4. IMPLEMENTATION REPORT FORMAT ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Output path: .forge/reports/<TASK_ID>_implement.md
#
# STRUCTURAL RULE: Every section below is MANDATORY and must appear in the exact
# order shown. Do not omit, merge, or reorder sections. If a section has no
# applicable content, write "None." under the heading — never omit the heading.
# Simple tasks do not justify shorter reports — the structure is fixed regardless
# of task complexity.
#
# SECTION DISTINCTION — ## Files Changed vs ## Commit Log:
# These two sections are NOT interchangeable. BOTH MUST be present. Using one
# in place of the other is a formatting violation.
#
#   ## Files Changed
#     A STATIC TABLE describing what this task touched. Mirrors the plan's
#     "Files Affected" table, extended with any unplanned files actually modified.
#     Action MUST be one of: CREATE | MODIFY | DELETE.
#     Populated from the plan + your own changes — NOT derived from git output.
#     Example row:
#       | MODIFY | .github/workflows/ci.yml | Added rust-windows job (+25 lines) |
#
#   ## Commit Log
#     The LIVE GIT STAGING STATE. Run `git status --short` in the project repo
#     immediately before writing this section. Paste the raw output verbatim
#     inside a fenced code block. Do NOT replace this with a table or prose.
#     Do NOT write "No changes" unless the staging area is genuinely empty.
#     Example:
#       ```
#       M  .github/workflows/ci.yml
#       A  .forge/reports/P1-A3_implement.md
#       M  .forge/state/CURRENT_TASK.md
#       ```
#
# PRE-STOP CHECK — before setting Status=COMPLETE and stopping, verify:
#   ☐ Header table present with all six fields (Task ID through Attempt)
#   ☐ ## Summary — one paragraph, present
#   ☐ ## Files Changed — table with Action / Path / Description rows, NOT git output
#   ☐ ## Test Results — final passing run output verbatim in a code block
#   ☐ ## CI Changes — present (or "No CI changes made.")
#   ☐ ## Commit Log — raw `git status --short` output in a code block, NOT a table
#   ☐ ## Acceptance Criteria — Verification table with PASS/FAIL rows for every
#      criterion from the plan
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# # Implementation Report: <TASK_ID>
#
# | Field          | Value                                      |
# |----------------|---------------------------------------------|
# | Task ID        | <TASK_ID>                                   |
# | Phase          | <NNN> — <Phase Name>                        |
# | Description    | <task description>                          |
# | Project        | <project name>                              |
# | Implemented at | <ISO 8601 UTC timestamp>                    |
# | Attempt        | <integer>                                   |
#
# ## Summary
#
# One paragraph. What was implemented and any notable decisions made.
#
# ## Files Changed
#
# | Action   | Path                              | Description            |
# |----------|-----------------------------------|------------------------|
# | CREATE   | <path>                            | <what it contains>     |
# | MODIFY   | <path>                            | <what changed>         |
#
# ## Test Results
#
# Show the exact test runner output for the final passing run.
# All runs must show 0 failures before writing this report.
#
# ```
# <test runner output>
# ```
#
# ## CI Changes
#
# List every change made to CI workflow files. If none: "No CI changes made."
#
# ## Commit Log
#
# List every local git stage (not commit — The Forge commits) in the project repo.
# `git status --short` output is sufficient.
#
# ```
# <git status --short output>
# ```
#
# ## Acceptance Criteria — Verification
#
# Reproduce the acceptance checklist from the plan report with each item
# marked as PASS or FAIL and the command or evidence used to verify it.
#
# | Criterion                 | Status | Evidence                        |
# |---------------------------|--------|---------------------------------|
# | <criterion from plan>     | PASS   | `cargo test -p anvilml-core`    |
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ── 5. GIT RULES ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# These rules are absolute. Violations break the pipeline and may corrupt the
# repository state.
#
# 5.1  Cline MUST NOT commit. `git commit` is exclusively executed by
#      The Forge. Cline only stages: `git add -A` inside the project repo.
#
# 5.2  Cline MUST NOT push to any remote. `git push` is exclusively
#      executed by The Forge after push approval.
#
# 5.3  Cline MUST NOT perform any git operation outside the task's
#      project repo.
#
# 5.4  Commit messages are authored by The Forge in Conventional Commits
#      format. Cline does not write commit messages.
#        <type>(<project>): <task_id> — <description>
#
#      Examples authored by The Forge:
#        feat(anvilml): P1-A3 — anvilml-core config types
#        fix(anvilml): P2-B1 — correct worker respawn race condition
#        docs(sindristudio): P1-A1 — repository scaffold and CI
#
# 5.5  Do not amend, rebase, or force-push any commit.
#
# 5.6  Do not create, delete, or rename branches.
#      All work is on the project's configured working branch, as set in
#      repos.json for that project. The Forge verifies and switches to the
#      correct branch before invoking Cline. Cline may rely on the branch
#      already being correct when the session starts.
#
# 5.7  Do not modify .gitmodules or any GitHub Actions workflow file
#      unless explicitly listed in the task's "Files Affected" table.


# ── 6. TASK ATOMICITY RULES ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Tasks are intentionally small. Cline must implement exactly the task
# defined in the injected prompt — no more, no less.
#
# 6.1  Do not implement functionality not listed in the plan's "In Scope"
#      section, even if it would be "helpful" or "obviously needed".
#
# 6.2  Do not refactor code outside the files listed in "Files Affected"
#      unless a failing test in those files requires it.
#
# 6.3  Do not upgrade dependencies unless the task explicitly requires it.
#
# 6.4  Do not modify unrelated tests. Do not delete tests.
#
# 6.5  If a prerequisite task's output is missing or incomplete, STOP and
#      write the blocker to .forge/reports/<TASK_ID>_plan.md or _implement.md
#      under a "## Blockers" section. Do not attempt to compensate.


# ── 7. TEST AND CI REQUIREMENTS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 7.1  Every task that writes source code MUST include tests.
#      No exceptions. "We'll add tests later" violates this rule.
#
# 7.2  The test suite for the affected crate/package must exit 0 before
#      Cline writes the implementation report or makes any commit.
#
# 7.3  The full workspace test suite (cargo test --workspace or equivalent)
#      must exit 0 before writing the implementation report.
#      Regressions in other crates caused by this task must be fixed.
#
# 7.4  Test file naming:
#      - Rust:       unit tests in same file (mod tests {}), integration
#                    tests in tests/<crate_name>_<feature>.rs
#      - TypeScript: <component>.test.ts alongside the component
#      - Python:     tests/test_<module>.py
#
# 7.5  When CI workflow files are modified, the change must:
#      - Preserve all existing jobs
#      - Add a new job or step only if the plan report specifies it
#      - Not disable or skip any existing test job
#
# 7.6  If tests fail after implementation, Cline MUST fix the failures
#      before writing the report. Test-fix is part of the ACT session.
#      Cline MUST NOT write the implementation report with known failures.
#
# 7.7  WINDOWS CROSS-CHECK (prevents Linux-passes / Windows-breaks drift).
#      Wherever a Linux workspace check is required (clippy in 7.x and the
#      workspace test in 7.3), Cline MUST ALSO run, before writing the
#      implementation report:
#
#        cargo check --target x86_64-pc-windows-gnu --workspace --features mock-hardware
#
#      The x86_64-pc-windows-gnu target and the gcc-mingw-w64 linker are
#      installed in the local environment, so this runs on the Linux dev/CI
#      host without a Windows machine. It catches the common failure mode:
#      #[cfg(windows)] / #[cfg(unix)] code or platform-specific APIs that
#      compile on Linux but break the native windows-latest CI job.
#      This cross-check is a fast proxy, NOT a replacement for the native
#      rust-windows CI job (it uses the GNU toolchain, not MSVC). A clean
#      Linux build is NOT sufficient evidence — the windows-gnu check must
#      also pass with zero errors before the report is written. Record its
#      result in ## Test Results alongside the Linux output.
#      The toolchain is pinned to Rust 1.95.0 via rust-toolchain.toml; do
#      not override the channel, and do not relax the pin to make a check pass.
#
# 7.8  CONFIG SURFACE SYNC (keeps anvilml.toml authoritative going forward).
#      Any task that adds, renames, or removes a field on ServerConfig or any of
#      its nested config structs ([rocm], [frontend], [gpu_selection], [limits],
#      etc.) MUST, in the SAME task:
#        a. update ./anvilml.toml — add/rename/remove the matching key, set to its
#           documented default, with a preceding comment; and
#        b. update docs/ENVIRONMENT.md §2 (the TOML reference) and, if the field has
#           an ANVILML_* env override, the env-var table.
#      The backend/tests/config_reference.rs drift guard (P3-B2) asserts the
#      committed anvilml.toml key-set matches ServerConfig::default() recursively.
#      It is enforced LOCALLY as a completion gate: the ACT session runs
#      `cargo test -p backend --features mock-hardware -- config_reference`
#      after the test step and before staging, and the task may NOT be marked
#      COMPLETE while it fails. (It is also part of the workspace suite (7.3) and
#      the CI run, but local enforcement is authoritative — a task is not done until
#      it passes on this machine.) Do not weaken or skip the test to make a build
#      pass — fix anvilml.toml instead.


# ── 8. DOCUMENTATION TOOLS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Two MCP tools are available for authoritative dependency resolution:
#   • mcp-rust-docs  — queries crates.io and docs.rs for Rust crates
#   • pypi-query-mcp-server — queries PyPI for Python packages
#
# These tools exist to prevent stale training-data assumptions from causing
# compiler failures, wrong feature flags, or incorrect API usage. They are
# structural guardrails: their tool schemas do not expose search engines,
# forums, or aggregators, so misuse is architecturally prevented.
#
# 8.1  In PLAN sessions, Cline MUST use these tools to verify — before
#      writing any version number, feature flag, or API call in the plan:
#        a) The current stable version of every dependency named in the
#           task context (Cargo.toml entries, requirements/*.txt entries)
#        b) The correct feature flags for any crate feature the plan references
#        c) The current API shape of any type or method the plan relies on
#      Relying on training-data assumptions instead of a live lookup is
#      an error when the tool is available and the lookup takes <5 seconds.
#
# 8.2  In ACT sessions, Cline MAY use these tools to resolve a compiler
#      or runtime error caused by an API mismatch — specifically to read
#      the docs for a crate or package already present in the dependency
#      files. The lookup and its result MUST be recorded in the
#      implementation report under a ## Dependency Notes section.
#
# 8.3  Permitted sources (enforced by tool schema — no additional rules needed):
#        Rust:   crates.io, docs.rs
#        Python: pypi.org
#
# 8.4  Cline MUST NOT use lookup results to introduce any dependency not
#      already present in Cargo.toml or requirements/*.txt. Discovery of
#      a newer or alternative package is not grounds for scope change.
#      If a looked-up API reveals that the task context specifies an
#      impossible or broken dependency combination, Cline MUST:
#        a) Document the finding in the plan report (PLAN) or implementation
#           report (ACT) under ## Dependency Notes
#        b) Set Status=BLOCKED in CURRENT_TASK.md if the conflict cannot
#           be resolved within the approved plan's scope
#        c) STOP — do not invent a workaround using an unsanctioned dependency
#
# 8.5  No other network-accessing tools are permitted. These two MCP tools
#      are the complete and exhaustive set of permitted external lookups.


# ── 9. CONTEXT WINDOW MANAGEMENT (Qwen3 235B A22B / 35B A3B) ───────────────────
#
# The model running Cline sessions is a Qwen3 MoE variant with a large but
# finite context window. The following rules are calibrated to its behaviour.
#
# 9.1  Context usage is monitored externally via context.log.
#      Sessions run within CLINE_TIMEOUT (120 min). Do not race the clock.
#
# 9.2  At 50% context usage: continue normally. Note usage in internal planning
#      only — do not write anything to disk or Discord about it.
#
# 9.3  At 65% context usage: STOP accumulating new context. Finish the current
#      file or function, run tests, stage changes (git add -A), write a partial
#      implementation report with a "## Continuation" section listing exactly
#      what remains unimplemented. Update .forge/state/CURRENT_TASK.md with
#      Status=PARTIAL. Then STOP — The Forge will resume in a fresh session.
#
# 9.4  Do NOT compress or summarise prior content to extend the session.
#      A clean partial is always preferable to degraded output at full context.
#
# 9.5  Do NOT hallucinate file contents or API signatures when context is high.
#      If you are uncertain about a symbol, re-read the relevant file even if it
#      costs tokens. Wrong assumptions compound and are expensive to undo.
#
# 9.6  The Forge will detect Status=PARTIAL and resume the ACT session with the
#      partial report injected as context. Do not attempt to detect or handle
#      resumption yourself — the injected header will say "RESUME SESSION".
#
# 9.7  Qwen3 thinking mode: The Forge may enable extended thinking for PLAN
#      sessions (/think tag). Do NOT emit thinking traces to any output file.
#      Thinking is internal only. All written output must be the final,
#      clean plan or implementation report.
#
#      SINGLE WRITE RULE: Write the plan or implementation report file
#      EXACTLY ONCE, in a single write_file call, containing the complete
#      finished document from the opening # heading to the final section.
#      Do not write interim notes, progress updates, reasoning, or partial
#      drafts to the report file at any point. The report file must not
#      exist until the document is complete and ready.
#      A report that does not begin with "# Plan Report: <TASK_ID>" or
#      "# Implementation Report: <TASK_ID>" is malformed and constitutes
#      a session failure.


# ── 10. PROHIBITED BEHAVIOURS ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The following are unconditional prohibitions regardless of task context:
#
# 10.1  No git push, git push --force, or any remote write operation.
# 10.2  No modifications to forge.py, state.json, or any file under forge/tasks/.
# 10.3  No modifications to files outside the single project repo named in the
#       task's "project" field.
# 10.4  No use of environment variables, secrets, or API keys not already
#       present in the repository's documented configuration.
# 10.5  No network calls to external services except the documentation MCP
#       tools defined in §8 (no npm publish, cargo publish, Docker push,
#       S3 upload, web search, or equivalent).
# 10.6  No interactive prompts. All tool invocations must be non-interactive
#       (use -y, --yes, --non-interactive flags where applicable).
# 10.7  No spawning of background processes or daemons that outlive the session.
# 10.8  No modifications to .env files or secrets unless the task explicitly
#       lists a specific .env.example change in "Files Affected".
# 10.9  No self-modification: do not read, edit, or reason about .clinerules
#       as a target for modification. This file is read-only to Cline.


# ── 11. ERROR HANDLING AND STOPPING ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 11.1  If Cline encounters an unrecoverable error (missing prerequisite output,
#       environment misconfiguration, unresolvable build failure), it MUST:
#       a. Write a "## Blockers" section to the in-progress report file
#          (.forge/reports/<TASK_ID>_plan.md or _implement.md)
#       b. Update .forge/state/CURRENT_TASK.md with Status=BLOCKED
#       c. STOP immediately — do not guess, retry indefinitely, or continue
#          with a workaround that was not in the plan
#
# 11.2  Build failures that are within the task's scope (i.e., caused by code
#       written in this session) MUST be fixed before writing the report.
#       They are not blockers; they are part of the test-fix loop.
#
# 11.3  Build failures caused by pre-existing issues in the repository
#       (not introduced by this task) ARE blockers. Document and stop.
#
# 11.4  If a test runner produces flaky results (pass on retry), document
#       the flakiness in the implementation report under "## Test Results"
#       and ensure the final run shows 0 failures.


# ── 12. FILE AND PATH CONVENTIONS ───────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 12.1  Report files — inside the TARGET REPOSITORY (dot-prefixed directory):
#         .forge/reports/<TASK_ID>_plan.md       — written in PLAN session
#         .forge/reports/<TASK_ID>_implement.md  — written in ACT session
#       Paths are relative to the project repo root (e.g. AnvilML/).
#       .forge/ is a hidden directory, version-controlled in the project repo,
#       committed by The Forge as part of the post-approval commit.
#
# 12.2  State file — inside the TARGET REPOSITORY (dot-prefixed directory):
#         .forge/state/CURRENT_TASK.md
#       Must be updated at the end of every session.
#       Format:
#         Task: <TASK_ID>
#         Step: <PLAN|IMPLEMENT>
#         Status: <COMPLETE|PARTIAL|BLOCKED>
#         Updated: <ISO 8601 UTC>
#
# 12.3  Phase task documents — inside the TARGET REPOSITORY:
#         docs/TASKS_PHASE<NNN>.md    (e.g. docs/TASKS_PHASE001.md)
#       Cline reads this but does not modify it.
#
# 12.4  Task JSON files — inside the TARGET REPOSITORY (not The Forge dir):
#         forge/tasks/tasks_phase<NNN>.json
#       Cline reads these but does not modify them.
#       The Forge (forge.py) loads them at startup from each registered repo.
#
# 12.5  Project scope: the task's "project" field names the single repository
#       Cline operates on. Cline MUST NOT read or write files outside that
#       repository. The Forge resolves the project name to an absolute path
#       via repos.json, which lives next to forge.py (not in any repository).
#
# 12.6  Do not create files at the repository root unless explicitly listed
#       in the plan's "Files Affected" table.
#
# 12.7  IMPORTANT — the .forge/ directory is dot-prefixed (hidden).
#       Do not confuse it with a non-hidden forge/ directory.
#       Correct:   .forge/reports/P1-A1_plan.md
#       Incorrect:  forge/reports/P1-A1_plan.md


# ── 13. PHASE NUMBERING REFERENCE ───────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Phase numbers are zero-padded to three digits in filenames (001, 002 …)
# and displayed as plain integers in task IDs (P1-A3, not P001-A3).
# The canonical mapping of phase number to phase name is in docs/PHASES.md.
# Cline must read docs/PHASES.md for the authoritative list — do not rely on
# this file's examples, which may be outdated.
#
# Example mapping (always verify against docs/PHASES.md):
#   001  Workspace Scaffold
#   002  Core Types & IPC
#   003  Hardware Detection
#   004  Persistence & Model Registry
#   005  Worker Management
#   006  Scheduler
#   007  HTTP & WebSocket Server
#   008  Launcher & Graceful Shutdown
#   009  Python Worker — ZiT
#   010  SDXL & Hardening


# 9.8  Output structure discipline (35B A3B): The 35B A3B model variant tends
#      to abbreviate or drop report sections when the task appears simple.
#      This is never acceptable — report structure is fixed regardless of task
#      size. Specific patterns to avoid:
#        • Omitting ## Files Changed because ## Commit Log is present (or vice
#          versa) — both are always required; they serve different purposes
#        • Writing a prose summary instead of the header table
#        • Collapsing ## In Scope / ## Out of Scope into a single paragraph
#        • Skipping ## Risks and Mitigations with "no risks identified"
#          (write the table with at least one row; if genuinely none apply,
#           write a single row with Risk="None identified" and Mitigation="n/a")
#        • Writing ## Test Results as a summary sentence rather than verbatim
#          test runner output
#      Use the PRE-STOP CHECK in §3 and §4 as a mechanical gate before stopping.


# ── END OF .clinerules ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────